@@eRakuen: The Failed Paradise@@N

South of Midgaard, beyond the Eccentric Woodland, lies @@yRakuen@@N -- founded
on the belief that a city could be governed by beauty rather than force.
Its founding document, the @@ySouthward Compact@@N, was drafted as a deliberate
rejection of Midgaard's ledger culture.

@@gThe Paradise Thesis@@N

Haven-Architect @@gElys Savan@@N argued that a city built around shared surplus
-- common orchards, cooperative waterworks, rotating stewardship -- would
outperform any system of adjudicated obligations. For a generation, it
worked. The orchards took root, the cisterns flowed, and the Festival of
Ever-Bloom celebrated genuine prosperity.

@@yThe Five Eras@@N

In its @@yfounding generation@@N, Rakuen thrived. During the @@ystandardization
century@@N, its Garden Ledger drew admiring delegations from Kiess. The
@@ycontainment era@@N saw Midgaard quietly use Rakuen as a resettlement valve.
The @@yAsh-and-Iron decades@@N poisoned cisterns, killed orchards, and forced
the paradise city to adopt ration towers, labor drafts, and salvage courts.
The @@ymodern era@@N is defined by three refused petitions for annexation.

@@rThree Petitions, Three Refusals@@N

The @@rSouthmark Petition@@N argued moral obligation; Midgaard cited incompatible
accounting. The @@rAsh Plea@@N opened with a death count; Midgaard cited route
instability. The @@rIron Compact Appeal@@N proposed incremental integration over
twenty-five years; Midgaard refused on constitutional grounds, arguing that
absorbing Rakuen would require dissolving its founding charter.

@@dA City Ungovernable@@N

Rakuen has refused every attempt by the five-city institutions to define it.
Cracked Promise Stones still mark the boundaries of a paradise that exists
now only in ceremony. The Bloom Pavilion's living roof of trained ivy is
maintained as proof that something still grows as the founders intended.
The Ember Wardens patrol. The Garden Ledger Clerks guard records that
contradict the official story. Rakuen persists: proud, exhausted, and
ungovernable.
